Marvin Solomon:

Hi.  I disagree.  If a port is "well known" then it should be listed
in "Assigned Numbers" (RFC-960 is the most recent edition).  People
are certainly allowed to make other arrangements for using ports, but
such ad hoc arrangements do not make the ports "well known".  The
purpose of the "Assigned Numbers" document is exactly to keep track of
those Internet parameters (including ports) that are expected to be
well known.  If some protocol or service is a common convention or
standard of some kind for even a small fraction of the Internet
community why not document it publicly (in an RFC) and have one of the
low numbered ports assigned to it?

--jon.
